"{\"correct\": \"no\", \"explanation\": \"The OneHotEncoder in scikit-learn does not handle categorical variables that are not strings or integers, but in this case, it's fine. However, the main issue here is that the GaussianNB algorithm in scikit-learn expects the input data to be numeric and have a Gaussian distribution. The OneHotEncoder will output a matrix with binary values (0s and 1s) which does not follow a Gaussian distribution. Therefore, using GaussianNB with categorical data that has been one-hot encoded is not the best choice.\", \"patch\": \"26c26\\n< ('algo', GaussianNB())\\n---\\n> ('algo', MultinomialNB())\"}"